    "question_id" : 43995886,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>And so I see from other answers that there are several ways of dealing with it. But I don't believe this. It has to be reduced into one way. I love IDE but, but if I follow the IDE steps provided from different answers I know this is not the fundamental algebra. My error looked like:</p>\n<pre><code>* What went wrong:\nExecution failed for task ':compileJava'.\n&gt; Could not target platform: 'Java SE 11' using tool chain: 'JDK 8 (1.8)'.\n</code></pre>\n<p>And the way to solve it scientifically is:</p>\n<pre><code>vi build.gradle\n</code></pre>\n<p>To change from:</p>\n<pre><code>java {\n    sourceCompatibility = JavaVersion.toVersion('11')\n    targetCompatibility = JavaVersion.toVersion('11')\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>to become:</p>\n<pre><code>java {\n    sourceCompatibility = JavaVersion.toVersion('8')\n    targetCompatibility = JavaVersion.toVersion('8')\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>The scientific method is that method that is open for argumentation and deals on common denominators.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 19748211,
      "reputation" : 549,
      "user_id" : 14460109,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GgX5in6_v8SxkAgZTzWajssWZMU7hU_-D4foFz5=k-s256",
      "display_name" : "Yasiru Padmasiri",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/14460109/yasiru-padmasiri"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1604648699,
